<HEADLINE>
<P>
BALZER ON SPIRITS: WYBOROVA VODKA 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Robert Lawrence Balzer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
VODKA IS A BEVERAGE that generally isn't associated with Poland. Therefore, it 
may be of some surprise that that country produces Europe's best-selling vodka: 
Wyborowa. In previous centuries, when Polish royalty called for the best vodka 
they asked for wyborowa, meaning "the choicest." 
</P>
<P>
Today, Europeans also are asking for the choicest. Wyborowa (pronounced 
Vee-ba-rova) is a 100% rye grain spirit, produced with soft water from deep 
artesian wells, which accounts for its crystalline purity and exceptionally 
clean smoothness. 
</P>
<P>
Wyborowa ($12.95 for 750 milliliters 80-proof) begins with the most select rye 
grain that comes from thousands of small farms; during malting (soaking, 
sprouting and kiln-drying the grains) in wellspring water, starch is converted 
to glucose. Then fermentation begins with triple distillation of the mash to 
follow at high proof to extract all congeners, or impurities, until the 
resulting liquid is colorless, odorless, and by official definition, without 
distinctive character, aroma or taste. 
</P>
<P>
The state-owned and -operated Polmos distillery is in Poznan in central Poland 
and has been producing Wyborowa for centuries. Although vodka is usually made 
with grains such as rye and wheat, I was told that 75% of all vodka production 
in Poland uses potatoes. I wondered how potato vodka would taste. I found my 
answer through a blind tasting of the Wyborowa (rye) and the Luksusowa 
(potato), both at 80-proof. To the eye and the nose, there is no difference at 
all. To the palate, yes, a minimal, but detectable difference. Neither I nor 
two of my colleagues were able to identify which was which, only that one was 
softer. That turned out to be the potato vodka, ($15.99 for 750 milliliters 
80-proof). 
</P>
<P>
Centuries ago, devotees stashed their vodka in snowbanks. Now you can store it 
in your freezer, ready at any time to be served icy cold, neat -- in the Polish 
tradition. Na zdrowie! (Nah-stro-vyeh) "To your health!" Robert Lawrence Balzer 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column 
</P>
</TYPE>
