<HEADLINE>
<P>
THE COMEBACK KID 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
An unfortunate error in Pat H. Broeske's intriguing article about the ageless 
writer Charles Bennett ("Now Here's a Real Comeback," Sept. 30): Scratch "Anna 
Ondry." She never existed. 
</P>
<P>
Hitchcock's choice for leading woman in "Blackmail" was the well-known German 
actress Anny Ondra. 
</P>
<P>
Ondra's private life was highlighted by her marriage to German heavyweight 
boxer Max Schmeling. Schmeling is remembered as the fighter who knocked out Joe 
Louis, only to be cut down himself in the first round of their rematch. 
</P>
<P>
All that may be far less significant than the revelation long after the end of 
World War II that Schmeling risked his life during the horrors of Nazi Germany 
to hide and help save countless Jews who otherwise would almost certainly have 
perished during the Holocaust. 
</P>
<P>
ALAN HARVEY 
</P>
<P>
Arleta 
</P>
</TEXT>
