89 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
A YOUNG MILLIONAIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
I stand up and salute Shane Black ("Portrait of a Young Millionaire," by James 
Greenberg, Aug. 19). 
</P>
<P>
He and the other writers who are cashing in on the era of spec scripts deserve 
every penny not skimmed by 10-percenters and greedy producers. 
</P>
<P>
I was writing on spec long before Bart Simpson was born, and I've also been 
rejected more than Elvis has been sighted, so I can appreciate this new wave of 
hope for the unknown and unrecognized. 
</P>
<P>
I just need to know: Who do these writers know that I don't know? 
</P>
<P>
JON BLOSDALE 
</P>
<P>
Arleta 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA100790-0126 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 288922 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
October 7, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Magazine; Page 4; Magazine Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
77 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
A YOUNG MILLIONAIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Your article on scriptwriter Shane Black and the Pad O' Guys made it instantly 
clear to me why current American films are in the hammerlock of a macho-buddy, 
total-whammo, blast-'em, kick-'em-in-the-groin mentality. These creative 
talents have been raised on the culture of their times: pop fiction and TV. 
Their creative output is just so much fast-pizza delivery: Load it up, get it 
there fast, and don't pick up the empty boxes. 
</P>
<P>
REGINA M. MORIN 
</P>
<P>
San Diego 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Letter to the Editor 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA100790-0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 288923 </DOCID>
<DATE>
<P>
October 7, 1990, Sunday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Magazine; Page 4; Magazine Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
130 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
A YOUNG MILLIONAIRE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
It is 1990, isn't it? I wasn't sure after I read the article on Shane Black and 
all the other nice, young, white, male successful screenwriters. For some crazy 
reason, I figured that in 1990 we must have a few females and minority groups 
represented in one end of the business or another. 
</P>
<P>
But Greenberg's article did not mention one female or ethnic group in any facet 
of the industry -- no writers, no agents, no producers, nobody. Was there no 
one who suggested to your writer that in the year 1990 he might be able to find 
a few newly successful female or minority writers? And if he couldn't, wouldn't 
that be a fact worthy of mention? 
</P>
<P>
It was an interesting contrast to Robin Wright's excellent article on South 
Africa, to say the least. 
</P>
<P>
NANCY RECHTMAN 
</P>
<P>
Van Nuys 
</P>
</TEXT>
