<P>
</P>
<P>
RAMBLING AND WRECKING 
</P>
<P>
No. 23 Georgia Tech (4-0) has played aggressive defense all season, but the 
Yellow Jackets outdid even themselves against Atlantic Coast Conference 
opponent Maryland in a 31-3 victory. The Georgia Tech defense, which has not 
allowed a touchdown this season, sacked quarterback Scott Zolak seven times in 
the first half and 11 times in the game, bringing the four-game total to 23 
sacks and 12 interceptions. Zolak, sacked for losses totaling 65 yards, passed 
for 192 yards, almost 100 yards below his average, was intercepted once and was 
removed in the fourth quarter. Georgia Tech has won 11 of 12 and eight in a 
row. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
BIG PLAYS 
</P>
<P>
Tommy Vardell's fourth one-yard touchdown run, with 36 seconds left, gave 
Stanford a 36-31 victory over No. 1 Notre Dame. Quarterback Jason Palumbis kept 
the Cardinal's game-winning drive alive when he ran for two yards and a first 
down on a fourth-down play. The victory was Stanford's first over Notre Dame 
since a 24-14 win at Palo Alto, Calif., in 1963. 
</P>
<P>
Jim Von Wyl's third field goal, a 30-yarder with three seconds remaining, gave 
No. 5 Auburn a 16-14 victory over Louisiana Tech. 
</P>
<P>
Jeff Shudak's 53-yard field goal with 18 seconds left gave Iowa State a 34-34 
tie with Kansas. Shudak became Iowa State's career kick-scoring leader with 222 
points, breaking the mark of 214 points set by Alex Giffords from 1979-82. Iowa 
State's all-time scoring leader is Dexter Green with 228 points. 
</P>
<P>
Oklahoma's freshman quarterback, Cale Gundy, came off the bench and completed a 
52-yard pass play to Adrian Cooper as time ran out in the first half to bring 
the Sooners into a 14-14 tie. Oklahoma went on to win, 31-17. 
</P>
<P>
Iowa linebacker Melvin Foster had 20 tackles, an interception that the Hawkeyes 
turned into a touchdown and made a key fourth-down stop in the fourth quarter 
in a 12-7 victory over Michigan State. 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
IN QUOTES 
</P>
<P>
Stanford Coach Dennis Green, on running back Tommy Vardell, who scored on four 
one-yard touchdown runs in the Cardinal's 36-31 upset of No. 1 Notre Dame: "We 
call number 44 Touchdown Tommy. We know he's going to get the ball, you know 
he's going to get the ball, and we want to see you try to stop him." 
</P>
<P>
Said Notre Dame Coach Lou Holtz: "I don't know if I've ever been in a loss this 
difficult." 
</P>
<P>
Maryland Coach Joe Krivak, on the 31-3 loss to Georgia Tech: "That is as 
probably as good a licking as we have taken all season. I think it was in every 
phase of the game. They ran the ball, they threw when they wanted to and we 
couldn't handle their pass rush." 
</P>
<P>
Houston's David Klingler, after completing 35 of 68 passes in a 31-15 victory 
over Baylor: "I throw 300 balls a day and this was a good warmup for me. Still 
I was dragging there late. I was hoping I'd get hooked." 
</P>
<P>
Louisiana Tech linebacker Myron Baker, after a 16-14 loss to Auburn: "It's hard 
to tell how good Auburn is, but if they're a top-five team then we should be 
right behind them." 
</P>
<P>
Georgia Coach Ray Goff, after a 34-3 loss to Clemson: "I don't think I could 
tell you all my feelings right now. Obviously, I am disappointed. We just got 
whipped. You can write all the ifs, ands or buts you want, but the bottom line 
is that Clemson lined up and whipped us." 
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
